\begin{verbatim}
SweptSine(F, tstart, duration, fstart, fend, type)
\end{verbatim}
Struct to define a swept sine excitation signal

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{F::Real}: Amplitude of the force [N]


\item \texttt{tstart::Real}: Starting time of the excitation [s]


\item \texttt{duration::Real}: Duration of the excitation [s]


\item \texttt{fstart::Real}: Starting frequency [Hz]


\item \texttt{fend::Real}: Ending frequency [Hz]


\item \texttt{type::Symbol}: Type of sweep

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:lin} - linear (default)


\item \texttt{:quad} - quadratic


\item \texttt{:log} - logarithmic

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{zero\_end::Bool}: Boolean to set the excitation to 0 at the end of the duration (default = true)

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
GaussianPulse(F, tstart, duration, fc)
\end{verbatim}
Struct to define a Gaussian pulse excitation signal

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{F::Real}: Amplitude of the force [N]


\item \texttt{tstart::Real}: Starting time of the excitation [s]


\item \texttt{duration::Real}: Duration of the excitation [s]


\item \texttt{fc::Real}: Center frequency of the pulse [Hz]


\item \texttt{precision::Real}: Precision of the pulse (default = 4.)

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

The precision parameter calibrates the standard deviation of the pulse, so that the duration = n x σ, within some precision. If n = 1.96 then the confidence interval of the Gaussian distribution is 95\%. To do so, we compute n so that at t = duration = n x σ , the amplitude of F x exp(-0.5*(t - duration/2)\^{}2/sigma\^{}2) = 10\^{}(-precision)

\begin{verbatim}
ColoredNoise(F, color)
\end{verbatim}
Struct to define a colored noise excitation signal

\textbf{Fields}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{F::Real}: Mean amplitude of the force [N]


\item \texttt{tstart::Real}: Starting time of the excitation [s]


\item \texttt{duration::Real}: Duration of the excitation [s]


\item \texttt{σ::Real}: Target standard deviation of the colored noise


\item \texttt{color::Symbol}: Color of the noise

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:white} (default)


\item \texttt{:pink}


\item \texttt{:blue}


\item \texttt{:brown}


\item \texttt{:purple}

\end{itemize}

\item \texttt{band\_freq::AbstractVector}: Frequencies used to defined the bandpass filter applied to the colored noise

\end{itemize}

